Reference-contexts: 1 Introduction When we regard the plane as a set of points, we can define various geometric properties of subsets of the plane|connectedness, convexity, area, diameter, etc.; for a review of geometric properties that are of interest in image analysis and computer vision, see <ref> [1] </ref>. Most of these properties can be generalized to fuzzy subsets of the plane; for reviews of the literature on fuzzy geometry see [2, 3]. The plane can also be regarded as a set of lines; this "dual" viewpoint plays an important role in projective geometry [4]. <p> This allows us to define fuzzy connectedness, fuzzy convexity, etc. for fuzzy sets of lines; we recall <ref> [1] </ref> that a fuzzy set is fuzzy connected (convex) iff its level sets are all connected (convex), so that the results in Sections 2.2-3 can be used to characterize fuzzy connectedness (convexity) for fuzzy sets of lines.
